        info: "<p>The interface command <strong><code>ip ospf network point-to-point</code></strong> forces an Ethernet interface to behave as a point-to-point OSPF link instead of broadcast. Used when exactly two routers share a /30 or /31 Ethernet link — skips DR/BDR election entirely and converges faster.</p><p><strong>Benefits:</strong> (1) No DR/BDR election (saves ~40 seconds on initial adjacency). (2) No wait for DR to become stable before Full state. (3) Simpler operation (no <code>show ip ospf neighbor</code> confusion from DROther states). (4) Slightly less Hello overhead (no election messaging). (5) In large networks with many P2P Ethernet links, consistent network type simplifies design.</p><p><strong>Must be configured on BOTH sides</strong> — mismatched network types (one side broadcast, one side point-to-point) prevents neighbor formation. Cisco best practice: always match network types explicitly on every link between two routers on a small subnet.</p><p><strong>Configuration:</strong></p><pre>interface GigabitEthernet0/0\n ip ospf network point-to-point\n ip ospf 1 area 0</pre><p><strong>Verification:</strong> After configuring, <code>show ip ospf interface Gi0/0</code> prints 'Network Type POINT_TO_POINT.' <code>show ip ospf neighbor</code> shows FULL/ -. If you see FULL/DR or FULL/BDR instead, the command did not apply or is only on one side.</p><p><strong>Warning:</strong> Do NOT use this on Ethernet segments with more than two OSPF routers — only one neighbor will be recognized, breaking OSPF for the rest.</p>",
