        id: "3.4.b.4",
        term: "P2P Hello timer (10 / 40)",
        weight: "med",
        info: "<p>On the <strong>point-to-point network type</strong>, the default <strong>Hello interval is 10 seconds</strong> and the <strong>Dead interval is 40 seconds</strong> (4x Hello). These match the defaults on broadcast networks — the timers are based on network speed assumptions, not specifically on whether a DR is elected.</p><p>Compare with NBMA network types (Frame Relay, X.25): Hello defaults to <strong>30 seconds</strong> and Dead to <strong>120 seconds</strong>. NBMA was originally designed for slower WAN links where less-frequent Hellos reduce overhead.</p><p><strong>When you see:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Serial HDLC/PPP:</strong> P2P, Hello 10, Dead 40.</li><li><strong>GRE tunnel:</strong> P2P, Hello 10, Dead 40.</li><li><strong>Ethernet (default):</strong> broadcast, Hello 10, Dead 40.</li><li><strong>Ethernet with <code>ip ospf network point-to-point</code>:</strong> P2P, Hello 10, Dead 40.</li><li><strong>Frame Relay main interface (default):</strong> NBMA, Hello 30, Dead 120.</li><li><strong>Frame Relay multipoint subinterface:</strong> NBMA, Hello 30, Dead 120.</li><li><strong>Frame Relay point-to-point subinterface:</strong> P2P, Hello 10, Dead 40.</li></ul><p><strong>Override with:</strong> <code>ip ospf hello-interval [seconds]</code> and <code>ip ospf dead-interval [seconds]</code> at the interface level. Both must match between neighbors. Verify with <code>show ip ospf interface [int]</code> — look for 'Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5.'</p>",
